
1.  What are Wrapper Classes?

Wrapper Classes are classes that convert primitive data types into objects.

Java Collections Framework works only with objects, so wrapper classes are used when object representation is required.

| Primitive Type | Wrapper Class |
| -------------- | ------------- |
| byte           | Byte          |
| short          | Short         |
| int            | Integer       |
| long           | Long          |
| float          | Float         |
| double         | Double        |
| char           | Character     |
| boolean        | Boolean       |

---

2. Why do we need Wrapper Classes?

  1. Collections require Objects

❌ Not Allowed

ArrayList<int> list = new ArrayList<>();


✅ Allowed

ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();


---

2. Utility Methods

Wrapper classes provide useful methods.

int num = Integer.parseInt("100");

System.out.println(num);
```

Output:
100


---

## Autoboxing

Automatic conversion of primitive type to wrapper object.

 Example
int num = 10;

Integer obj = num;

Java automatically converts int → Integer.

---

## Unboxing

Automatic conversion of wrapper object to primitive type.

 Example

Integer obj = 20;

int num = obj;


Java automatically converts Integer → int.

---

## Example of Autoboxing and Unboxing

```java
Integer a = 100; // Autoboxing

int b = a;       // Unboxing

System.out.println(b);
```

Output:

```java
100
```

---

## Common Methods of Wrapper Classes

### Integer.parseInt()

Converts String to int.

```java
int num = Integer.parseInt("123");
```

---

### Integer.valueOf()

Returns Integer object.

```java
Integer num = Integer.valueOf("123");
```

---

### toString()

Converts number to String.

```java
Integer num = 100;

String str = num.toString();
```

---

## Integer Caching (Important Interview Question)

Java caches Integer objects from **-128 to 127**.

### Example

```java
Integer a = 100;
Integer b = 100;

System.out.println(a == b);
```

Output:

```java
true
```

Because both objects use the cached value.

---

### Example

```java
Integer a = 200;
Integer b = 200;

System.out.println(a == b);
```

Output:

```java
false
```

Because new objects are created.

